fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let \{X_{n}:n\geq 1\} denote i.i.d. \mathcal {X}-valued r.v. with distribution P_{X}. Then,

 \begin {align*}  \lim _{n\to \infty }-\frac {1}{n}\log  p_{X^{n}}(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}) &= \lim _{n \to  \infty } -\frac {1}{n} \log  \prod _{i = 1}^{n} P_X(X_i) \\  &= \mathbb {E}_{X \sim  p_X}[-\log  p_X(X)] \\   &= H(X) \end {align*} 
Equivalently, for large n
   \begin {align*}     \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon    \end {align*} 
with high probability.

Fix an \epsilon >0. Then, an \epsilon -typical set with respect to the pmf p_{X}, denoted by A_{\epsilon }^{(n)}, is defined as
\left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon  \right \}
Alternatively,
A_{\epsilon ^{(n)}} = \left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  2^{-n(H(X) + \epsilon )} \leq  p_{X^n}(X^n) \leq  2^{-n(H(X) - \epsilon )}\right \}

For the other direction, suppose we have some R achievable. By definition, for all \epsilon  > 0, for all sufficiently large n there exists a [kak-0059] with parameters (n, \theta ) such that
         \begin {align*}           \frac {\log  \theta }{n} < R + \epsilon , \quad  \mathbb {P}(\text {error}) < \epsilon          \end {align*}       
      Use Fano's Inequality to show this is not possible.

